      "FacilityID": 1000101268,
      "SummaryText": "s hazard analysis; operating procedures; training; mechanical integrity; management of change; pre-startup safety review; compliance audits; incident investigations; employee participation; hot work permit; contractor management; and emergency planning and response. Throughout the plant, a hierarchy of controls has been implemented including hazard elimination, substitution, engineering controls, toxic gas sensors, administrative controls and personal protective equipment to minimize or eliminate exposure to hazards. Infrastructure security improvements at designated areas in the plant have been implemented that provide layers of protection against deliberate man-made incidents in accordance with applicable elements of U.S. Department of Homeland Security's CFATS Risk Based Performance Standards.\n\nIn the past five years, Thatcher Company has had one accidental release that resulted in a plant evacuation that occurred on June 19, 2019.  While moving a railcar with the trackmobile, it became uncoupled and rolled into a railcar that contained sulfur dioxide.  The momentum of the collision snapped the liquid SO2 unloading piping.  Hazmat personnel as well as the local fire fighters responded quickly.  Some plant personnel as well as some neighbors were treated locally.  There was one OSHA recordable injury.  NRC was notified that 1000-9000 lbs were released.  Final calculations showed that 9000 lbs were released.  There were 7 employee or contractor injuries on site, and 30 people off-site received medical treatments.\n \nIn an effort to maintain a safer workplace and being aware of the various chemicals handled and the hazardous nature of those chemicals, TCSLC has developed an Emergency Response Plan (SOP EHS-13).  The plan outlines actions and procedures to be utilized in the case of emergency action involving fires and the releases of, or substantial threats of releases of hazardous substances.  The plan addresses the following topics and procedures:\n?\tEmergency escap"
